---
import BaseLayout from "../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
import Header from "../../components/Header.astro";
import Footer from "../../components/Footer.astro";
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Range Case Study | Ross Lyall Portfolio"
  description="Case study for Range, a personal glucose and event logging app."
>
  <div class="page-shell">
    <Header />

    <main>
      <section class="case-hero case-hero--range">
        <a class="back-link" href="/">← Back to portfolio</a>

        <p class="eyebrow">Case Study / Home App / Personal Data</p>
        <h1>Range</h1>
        <p class="case-hero__lead">
          A personal glucose and event logging dashboard built to make readings,
          food, insulin and daily patterns easier to record, view and export.
        </p>

        <div class="case-meta">
          <span>React</span>
          <span>Supabase</span>
          <span>MacroDroid</span>
          <span>Edge Functions</span>
          <span>Personal pattern spotting</span>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="case-section case-showcase">
        <div class="mock-browser">
          <div class="mock-browser__bar">
            <span></span>
            <span></span>
            <span></span>
          </div>

          <div class="mock-screen" style="background: var(--range);">
            <span class="mock-screen__label">Range chart</span>
            <h2 class="mock-screen__heading">
              Readings, events and useful exports.
            </h2>

            <div class="mock-chart"></div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="mock-phone">
          <div class="mock-phone__screen">
            <div class="mock-phone__pill"></div>
            <div class="mock-phone__button">Record carbs</div>
            <div class="mock-phone__button">Fast acting</div>
            <div class="mock-phone__button">Background</div>
            <div class="mock-phone__button">Add note</div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="case-section case-overview">
        <div>
          <p class="eyebrow">The problem</p>
          <h2>
            Glucose data existed, but it was hard to connect it with real-life
            events.
          </h2>
        </div>

        <div class="case-copy">
          <p>
            Range was built around a personal need: glucose readings were
            available, but it was difficult to view them alongside the things
            that explain them — meals, fast acting insulin, background insulin,
            notes and eventually exercise.
          </p>

          <p>
            The goal was not to create a medical dosing tool. The aim was to
            build a private logging app for spotting patterns, exporting useful
            data and making it easier to discuss trends with health
            professionals.
          </p>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="case-section case-overview">
        <div>
          <p class="eyebrow">The solution</p>
          <h2>A simple dashboard for readings, events and useful exports.</h2>
        </div>

        <div class="case-copy">
          <p>
            Range collects glucose readings into Supabase, displays them on a
            clean chart and lets manual events be recorded separately. Carbs,
            fast acting insulin, background insulin and notes are treated as
            individual events rather than being bundled together.
          </p>

          <p>
            The app also includes a data page where a selected period can be
            exported as CSV or copied into a structured prompt for analysis and
            pattern discussion.
          </p>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="case-section">
        <div class="section-heading">
          <p class="eyebrow">Data flow</p>
          <h2>How the readings get into the app</h2>
          <p>
            The first working version uses a practical automation flow to move
            glucose readings from the phone into the database.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="flow-grid">
          <article class="flow-card">
            <span>01</span>
            <h3>Libre sensor</h3>
            <p>
              Glucose readings are captured from the sensor and made available
              through the phone setup.
            </p>
          </article>

          <article class="flow-card">
            <span>02</span>
            <h3>GlucoDataHandler</h3>
            <p>
              GlucoDataHandler provides the current glucose value that can then
              be picked up by phone automation.
            </p>
          </article>

          <article class="flow-card">
            <span>03</span>
            <h3>MacroDroid</h3>
            <p>
              MacroDroid watches for new readings and sends them to the app
              using an HTTP request.
            </p>
          </article>

          <article class="flow-card">
            <span>04</span>
            <h3>Supabase</h3>
            <p>
              A Supabase Edge Function receives the reading securely and stores
              it in the database.
            </p>
          </article>

          <article class="flow-card">
            <span>05</span>
            <h3>React dashboard</h3>
            <p>
              The dashboard reads the stored data and presents it as a simple
              chart, event log and exportable dataset.
            </p>
          </article>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="case-section">
        <div class="section-heading">
          <p class="eyebrow">Key features</p>
          <h2>What Range does</h2>
        </div>

        <div class="feature-grid">
          <article class="feature-card">
            <span>01</span>
            <h3>Live glucose chart</h3>
            <p>
              Shows glucose readings as a simple line graph with selectable
              periods such as today, the last hour and the last three hours.
            </p>
          </article>

          <article class="feature-card">
            <span>02</span>
            <h3>Manual event logging</h3>
            <p>
              Allows carbs, fast acting insulin, background insulin and notes to
              be recorded as separate phone-friendly events.
            </p>
          </article>

          <article class="feature-card">
            <span>03</span>
            <h3>Event markers</h3>
            <p>
              Shows events against the glucose chart without plotting them as
              glucose values, keeping the chart clean and readable.
            </p>
          </article>

          <article class="feature-card">
            <span>04</span>
            <h3>Data export</h3>
            <p>
              Exports readings and events for a selected period as CSV, making
              the data easier to keep, share or review.
            </p>
          </article>

          <article class="feature-card">
            <span>05</span>
            <h3>AI prompt support</h3>
            <p>
              Creates a structured prompt from selected data so patterns can be
              explored as discussion points, not medical instructions.
            </p>
          </article>

          <article class="feature-card">
            <span>06</span>
            <h3>Mobile-first recording</h3>
            <p>
              Keeps event recording simple with large buttons and one event
              recorded at a time.
            </p>
          </article>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="case-section case-overview">
        <div>
          <p class="eyebrow">Design thinking</p>
          <h2>
            The chart stays focused on glucose, while events explain the
            context.
          </h2>
        </div>

        <div class="case-copy">
          <p>
            One of the most important design decisions was to avoid plotting
            carbs or insulin as if they were glucose values. Instead, the chart
            remains a glucose line, with events shown as markers at the time
            they happened.
          </p>

          <p>
            This keeps the main graph understandable while still making it easy
            to see how food, insulin and notes line up with changes in readings.
          </p>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="case-section">
        <div class="section-heading">
          <p class="eyebrow">What I learned</p>
          <h2>Useful lessons from building it</h2>
        </div>

        <div class="lesson-list">
          <article>
            <h3>Health data needs careful wording</h3>
            <p>
              The app is deliberately framed around logging, exporting and
              spotting patterns rather than giving medical or dosing advice.
            </p>
          </article>

          <article>
            <h3>Automation can make a small app much more powerful</h3>
            <p>
              Using MacroDroid and Supabase turned the project from a manual
              logbook into a live personal dashboard.
            </p>
          </article>

          <article>
            <h3>Simple charts are often better</h3>
            <p>
              The most useful version was not the busiest one. A clean glucose
              line plus well-designed event markers made the data easier to
              understand.
            </p>
          </article>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="case-section case-next">
        <div>
          <p class="eyebrow">Future improvements</p>
          <h2>Where Range could go next</h2>
        </div>

        <ul>
          <li>Add walking and exercise periods to the chart.</li>
          <li>Improve long-term pattern summaries.</li>
          <li>Add more useful clinician-friendly exports.</li>
          <li>Refine the mobile installed-app experience.</li>
          <li>
            Build safer insight prompts focused on discussion, not decisions.
          </li>
        </ul>
      </section>
    </main>

    <Footer />
  </div>
</BaseLayout>
